Naveen, your Kandy visit to the Buddhist temple was very informative. I had an English Dictionary published by the British rulers from England in 1915-20 time when my father , then in primary school in Calicut, got the book as a gift from a Ceylon based relative. In that book there were many B&W pictures of various tourist places of Ceylon. The Tooth Temple of Kandy was prominently shown. In your video behind you I could spot the boundary wall of the Buddha Temple. It strongly resembles the boundary walls of the famous Tali Sivan Temple in Calicut, now called Kozhikode. The outline of the structure of the Buddha Temple building also resembles the outline of the Tiruvambadi temple at Thrissur. Interesting. Just like in Kerala, tea is the main beverage in Sri Lanka too and puttu and the kadalai curry and parotta too are like Kerala restaurants. Also coconut oil and coconuts are used in most dishes just like in Kerala and Coastal Karnataka.

Good informative video. Whether we like it or not.......Indian passport does not hold much value in the international scenario. That is the reason behind not being able to visit certain countries after getting a VISA stamp from Pakistan.  You mentioned about the 14 day tourist VISA and the stringent checks involved......the major point is that you need a person to stand guarantee for you in Pakistan during your 14 day stay.......that person is also put through rigorous checks in Pakistan......only then will that VISA be issued to the Indian. When I went I some how managed to finish my trip in the nick of the moment. The situation was not looking good in Delhi and Bengaluru......word was going around about deaths due to Covid in China and the US. I didnt wait to see what would happen eventually.......faked some family emergency ...... packed my bags and went back immediately to my family in the US. Whoah.....it turned out to be the best decision of my life.....else I would have been caught in India during the world wide lockdown.

Jog Falls is the second highest plunge waterfall in India located in Siddapura taluk Uttara Kannada district. It is a segmented waterfall which, depending on rain and season, becomes a plunge waterfall. Initially this train runs as 561/562 Mas to Cochin Cochin express from mas to Cochin which has been inaugurated on 1944. Till 1978 this mail runs as cochin express. This one (Vasco Londa) is straight route and the original line which was metre gauge earlier(till  90 s) from British Portuguese period  , The Dudhsagar station had scheduled halt for mg trains . For long time till  2000  reaching   Dudhsagar , even the bottom  of the falls ,was difficult task by road . This place near the bridge was accessible only by  train . Castlerock is the 1 st major  station of Karnataka  from Goa side .castle Rock is hill on Western ghats and since much of the Karnataka which this route covers is on the Deccan plateau so it is hill climbing from Kulem to Castlerock  . In The early 90 s Konkan railway laid the lines . They kept the alignment with Vasco Madgaon line.and so between Majorda and Madgaon both Konkan railway and South Western  railway line (earlier part of SCR) had same alignment .After Madgaon the Konkan railway turns right (South)towards Mangalore . The Castlerock station was in fact was entry for the Portuguese administered territory ( Goa)( in erstwhile times) , entry permits were checked since Karnataka and rest of India was British administered territory

I was travelled on this train from chennai to agra. Train was clean, 32 hours it took. I was travel in 3AC trip was amazing.

The locomotive that pulls this masterpiece is a WAP-7 (Wide gauge aka Broad gauge AC electric powered Passenger train 7th generation model introduced in 2001) engine made in Chittaranjan locomotive Works, Chittaranjan, West Bengal near Asansol. It was modified in India from the WAG-9 locomotive (gear ratio adjusted for fast speed Passenger version from heavy hauling Goods version) originally made by ABB Switzerland. The speed limit is set at 140 kmph as the safe limit. Another ABB Swiss made locomotive WAP-5 has an upper speed limit of 200 kmph but tested upto 160 kmph. The WAP-7 has a higher acceleration compared to WAP-5 which is designed for speed. The 7th generation engine is advantageous since it uses Head on Generation or HOG meaning all the power required for operating the train (the 6500 HP engine, power and Air-conditioning to the coaches comes from the Pantograph extracting the power from the 25 KV lines above the train. Non HOG locomotives requires another Diesel generator ( End on Generation) separately in the train for the power requirements. WAP-5 and WAP-7  are used to pull the premier trains like Rajdhanis, Shathabthis and Durontos and long haul non premier trains like the TN express.

The ghat range at 11:00 is actually the Vindhya Satpura mountain ranges that cut across east west in the state of Madhya Pradesh. Betul is actually on the line near the Satpura National Park. These remote and isolated forest areas has the most number of Tiger reserves in India.

When you travel north from Chennai during the non summer months you will feel a distinct cool air hitting you once you reach near the Hyderabad area. And on your reverse journey a warm humid air will hit you (irrespective of the time of year) forcing you to remove your jerkins and sweaters. This is because we are crossing a geographical line latitude wise approaching the sub tropical climate ( somewhat equal to Florida state in the US) zone from a tropical climate zone known as tropic of cancer. Chennai and Mexico city are in the same latitude giving that super hot and humid sticky weather conditions. The tropical of cancer line crosses exactly just north of Bhopal and there is a tourist place named by the same (TOC).

We all know that the northernmost end of the Indian subcontinent is Kashmir and the southern tip is Kanyakumari. Many may not be aware that Nagpur is in the dead center of India. Both left right and up and down.

The stop after Jhansi is Gwalior which if course reaches in the odd hour and everyone will be in deep sleep. Then after Agra cantt. it will make a brief stop in Hazrath Nizamuddin (outskirts of New Delhi) before reaching New Delhi Railway station (NDLS) by 7.00 AM.

Grand Trunk exp is a historic train and it connected Delhi and Madras even during the British rule in India. But after the introduction of the fastest Tamilnadu exp, the first preference is TN exp which has limited stoppages. And also, no stoppage between Chennai Central and Vijayawada. I think the GT exp takes 2 to 3 hrs more than the TN exp to reach New Delhi. But still GT exp is the legend of this route. Also, I like its name very much.

You said Erode loco is not the regular loco link to this train. But nowadays it may be due to WAP 7 locos replacing more no of WAP 4 locos.

But there were times when Erode WAP 4 was the regular link to the long distance trains bound for New Delhi like GT, TN, Kerala exp from Trivandrum, Andaman exp to Jammu Tawi and Ahmedabad bound Navjeevan exp through out the entire journey. Many times I have spotted ED loco coupled to these trains at Chennai central.

Chennai - New Delhi line was the major route for Erode WAP 4 locos. Many other South bound trains were also hauled by Erode WAP 4. For ex, Chandigarh - Madurai weekly SF exp via New Delhi, etc,..

I'm saying the time when WAP 4 locos were ruling the Indian Railways.

Love for GT exp from Erode.

Stopped only at Katpadi (9:15) to enable students studying in VMC (Kind courtesy Mr Jaffer Sheriff Hon railway minister), Jolarpet at 10:35 am, Bangarpet at 11:40 am, Bangalore Cantt at 12:35 pm and City station at 1:10 pm..

Old History of Pallavan Express. During MG Era, it was operated from Madras to Madurai and back similar to Vaigai which operates from Madurai to Madras and back. It was a non daily service similar to Vaigai. Vaigai will not be operated on Tuesdays and Pallavan was operated on all days. In Madurai it always comes in Platform 1 except on Tuesday. On Tuesdays, Pallavan will be received in Platform 3. Before that Vaigai rake which was maintained was waiting in Platform 1, used to run as Pallavan and workers used to carry the Boards and run towards platform 1 to fix it.

Due to operational difficulties and also issues in returning back to Chennai, it was cancelled and Vaigai was operated with 16 coaches and two YDM4A locos.

Later again it was introduced as Pallavan from Trichy and with rake sharing, which is continuing till now.

During MG Era, Vaigai was the only service runs end to end diesel up to Madras Egmore, where the engine got reversed as shot hood again to go to Madurai.

This was also had an unique green yellow livery with matching engine livery.

Bro..  you missed the opportunity to travel in this train 4 years back as it was hauled by WDG/WDM locos end to end from Egmore to Mannargudi.   Recently switched to AC loco due to completion of electrification of mainline.

Bro, you should surprise to note that Needamangalam Mannargudi section was a MG section which had Rajappaiyan Chavadi and Haridra Nadhi stations in between and one link passenger was operated along with Goods services as Mannargudi has FCI Godown and it is still there.  During 80s, train services stopped and this sections was abandoned and MG tracks were removed.  Later, when T R Balu was in Railway  coordination committee member, he took initiative to restore this section with extension to Pattukkottai, plan which is  approved and still on cards.  Now, this section is an electrified BG section with 4 express services and 2 passenger services.  Hope Mannargudi Pattukkottai connectivity will be restored soon.

I have recently travelled from Bangalore to chennai in DLT bus and had a horrible experience.
1. Bus got breakdown before soolagiri on highway. Alternate bus was not arranged and we passengers stopped government buses and reached our destinations.
2. Refund was not given to the passengers like me who didn't book the ticket through Red bus. When i asked to the DLT manager of chennai who booked my ticket, he said refund is only for Red bus booking and no refund for direct booking or booking through agent. When i argued he refused to answer and dropped the call.
3. Manager in chennai said not to book this bus directly as we don't get any support and he asked us to book from red bus.
4. There is a passenger who boarded the bus is not normal drunken etc.. They allocated the nearby berth to my cousin and we fought hard to get a alternate seat.
5. That drunken guy occupied both berth but still they allowed near passengers to board in kanchipuram and gave the same berth . Then he fought and asked for alternate berth.
6. Same berth was allocated to another guy who boarded in vellore. Literally they don't care about passengers and they focused only to fill that single seat though the co-passenger is drunken. The fight continued untill the bus breakdown.
7. The same bus had breakdown and pickup issues in the last two weeks which i just came to know by looking at the latest red bus review which wasn't available when i boarded the bus.

Never book this bus even if you are in terrible urgency. Because the bus we boarded at 8 in poonamalle didn't cross soolagiri by 2.30 PM .

Never book through agent as you won't get refund of your money in case of break down. And if you ask for refund then now on your call will be unanswered.
